{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17513281","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17513281"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:07:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:07:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12078"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12078","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12078"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.24,0.16,0.03,0.55,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4632"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104278"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4632","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4632"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12078"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86612"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1749"},{"type":"tags","id":"2136"},{"type":"tags","id":"2212"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7020"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7134"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15069"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37490"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104278","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/104278"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 26-year-old man presents to his General Practitioner complaining of groin pain. The man is a local football player and an active runner. The pain has progressively worsened over the last three months and is worse when sprinting and changing direction with force. When asked to specifically pinpoint the region of pain, the man vaguely gestures to the anterior groin region and bilaterally into the lateral groin region. On physical examination, there is localised tenderness over the pubic symphysis and pubic ramus. He has normal power with hip adduction and abduction. Plain radiographs show no abnormalities. An MRI scan shows bone oedema bilaterally along the pubic rami.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Stress fracture of the pubic rami","Adductor tendonitis","Adductor longus tear","Osteitis pubis","Abdominal rectus tear"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical picture and radiological findings fit a diagnosis of\u003Cstrong\u003E osteitis pubis. \u003C/strong\u003EThis is an idiopathic inflammatory condition of the pubic symphysis and ramus attributed to overuse associated with sports with high volumes of running and actions such as kicking that involve adduction/abduction. Pain is often vaguely described as occurring in the lower abdomen, hip and groin region unilaterally or bilaterally and exacerbated by sport and use. The pain is often insidious in nature, progressively worsening over time without rest. Palpation often finds tenderness of the pubic symphysis and ramus where microtears in the groin tendons and ligaments have occurred.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlain radiographs are often normal, with MRI being the best modality to diagnose the condition. Findings include demonstrate fluid in the pubic symphysis joint, bone oedema and/or visualisation of small tears of the adductor muscles. Management of this condition include activity modification, rest and NSAIDs for pain relief.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options are all differential diagnoses to consider. However, the MRI scan would likely be able to differentiate between these causes of the patient\u0027s pain. Similarly, it is unlikely that the \u003Cstrong\u003Eadductor longus tear\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003Eadductor tendonitis\u003C/strong\u003E would be bilateral and specifically cause pain in the pubic symphysis. If there was a \u003Cstrong\u003Estress fracture\u003C/strong\u003E, this would have been picked up on MRI.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Osteitis pubis is a condition classically cause by overuse injuries."],"references":["Johnson R. Osteitis pubis. Curr Sports Med Rep. 2003;2(2):98-102. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/12831666/","Meyers WC, Foley DP, Garrett WE, Lohnes JH, Mandlebaum BR. Management of severe lower abdominal or inguinal pain in high-performance athletes. PAIN (Performing Athletes with Abdominal or Inguinal Neuromuscular Pain Study Group). Am J Sports Med. 2000;28(1):2-8. doi: Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/10653536/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86612"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12078"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86612","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86612"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-31T02:56:36+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-31T02:57:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4632"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104278"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position"